Now we have to deal with the time variables JWAP and JWDP. Looking at the docs, we can see that these variables take on 286 values, so we definitely don’t have the time to hard code their levels.
That being said, I do see a pattern - (almost) every time the variable is incremented, the range is 5 minutes later. For some godforsaken reason, the range jumps 10 minutes when the variable goes from 7 -&gt; 8 and from 10 -&gt; 11. We can work around this quirk, but whoever is responsible deserves a lifetime of perpetually warm pillows. Shame.
Generally, if we set our clock to 12:02am (the middle range of the lowest value), we can add 5 times whatever value of JWAP/JWDP to get the time.
We can test our hypothesis by creating a function and testing

fix.time &lt;- function (time) {
  library(lubridate)

  is_zero &lt;- time == 0

  scnds_since_midnight &lt;- 120 + (time-1)*300 + ifelse(time &gt; 6, 300, 0) + ifelse(time &gt; 9, 300, 0)

  scnds_since_midnight[is_zero] &lt;- 0

  return(hms::as_hms(scnds_since_midnight))
}


